    "question_id" : 8969059,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I believe <code>@ElementCollection</code> is mainly for mapping non-entities (embeddable or basic) while <code>@OneToMany</code> is used to map entities. So which one to use depend on what you want to achieve. </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 299251,
      "reputation" : 342129,
      "user_id" : 605744,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a0a3a4200899708103f7430d87d56e24?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Tomasz Nurkiewicz",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/605744/tomasz-nurkiewicz"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 101,
    "last_activity_date" : 1327309452,
    "creation_date" : 1327309452,
    "answer_id" : 8969164,
    "question_id" : 8969059,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>@ElementCollection</code> allows you to simplify code when you want to implement one-to-many relationship with simple or embedded type. For instance in JPA 1.0 when you wanted to have a one-to-many relationship to a list of <code>String</code>s, you had to create a simple entity POJO (<code>StringWrapper</code>) containing only primary key and the <code>String</code> in question:</p>\n\n<pre><code>@OneToMany\nprivate Collection&lt;StringWrapper&gt; strings;\n\n//...\n\npublic class StringWrapper {\n  @Id\n  private int id;\n\n  private String string;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>With JPA 2.0 you can simply write:</p>\n\n<pre><code>@ElementCollection\nprivate Collection&lt;String&gt; strings;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Simpler, isn't it? Note that you can still control the table and column names using <code>@CollectionTable</code> annotation.</p>\n\n<h2>See also:</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Java_Persistence/ElementCollection\">Java Persistence/ElementCollection</a></li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 163820,
        "reputation" : 12522,
        "user_id" : 386201,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 75,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7f00de925967ccf41f64c2407b02d380?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Stuck",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/386201/stuck"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 9,
      "creation_date" : 1593679746,
      "post_id" : 8969169,
      "comment_id" : 110866418,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "... and you cannot query them on their own."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 277416,
      "reputation" : 694244,
      "user_id" : 571407,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2f0d9dec16bae1e06552af55ddefc11f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "JB Nizet",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/571407/jb-nizet"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 210,
    "last_activity_date" : 1429792607,
    "last_edit_date" : 1429792607,
    "creation_date" : 1327309494,
    "answer_id" : 8969169,
    "question_id" : 8969059,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>ElementCollection</code> is a standard JPA annotation, which is now preferred over the proprietary Hibernate annotation <code>CollectionOfElements</code>. </p>\n\n<p>It means that the collection is not a collection of entities, but a collection of simple types (Strings, etc.) or a collection of embeddable elements (class annotated with <code>@Embeddable</code>).</p>\n\n<p>It also means that the elements are completely owned by the containing entities: they're modified when the entity is modified, deleted when the entity is deleted, etc. They can't have their own lifecycle.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5727357,
      "reputation" : 409,
      "user_id" : 4523982,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5c1249220a41dc75f8bad5f492467f41?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "fidudidu",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4523982/fidudidu"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 8,
    "last_activity_date" : 1527755159,
    "creation_date" : 1527755159,
    "answer_id" : 50619866,
    "question_id" : 8969059,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>Basic or Embedded</strong>: @ElementCollection<br>\n<strong>Entities</strong>: @OneToMany or @ManyToMany</p>\n\n<p>@ElementCollection:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>the relation is managed (only) by the entity in which the relation is defined</li>\n<li>table contains id reference to the owning entity plus basic or embedded attributes</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>@OneToMany / @ManyToMany:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>can also be managed by the other entity</li>\n<li>join table or column(s) typically contains id references only</li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 13045725,
      "reputation" : 91,
      "user_id" : 9427636,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/aD6Kw.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "farshad-nsh",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/9427636/farshad-nsh"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1548399577,
    "creation_date" : 1548399577,
    "answer_id" : 54360409,
    "question_id" : 8969059,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>ElementCollection can override the mappings, or table for their collection, so you can have multiple entities reference the same Embeddable class, but have each store their dependent objects in a separate table.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 19034747,
      "reputation" : 74,
      "user_id" : 13896058,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-V_7lpRwNQ5Y/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/AMZuuck2TVhRC2NkuqmAh0PDwWfyqI2HsQ/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "PhongPhamIUH",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/13896058/phongphamiuh"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1609299245,
    "creation_date" : 1609299245,
    "answer_id" : 65501678,
    "question_id" : 8969059,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can use ElementCollection replace for you use @OneToMany. Example you can have one Project in many versions.</p>\n<pre><code>@ElementCollection\n@CollectionTable(name=&quot;versions&quot;,\njoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name=&quot;projectID&quot;))\n@LazyCollection(LazyCollectionOption.FALSE)\n@JoinColumn(name=&quot;version&quot;,nullable = false)\nprivate Set&lt;String&gt; versions;\n</code></pre>\n<p>You also can use @ElementCollection in mapping OGM for array in one collection.</p>\n<pre><code>@ElementCollection(fetch = FetchType.EAGER)\nprivate Set&lt;String&gt; researchAreas;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 24174596,
      "reputation" : 31,
      "user_id" : 18136172,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/IwAcC.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Karri Surya Venkata Prakash",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/18136172/karri-surya-venkata-prakash"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1649060766,
    "creation_date" : 1649060766,
    "answer_id" : 71734067,
    "question_id" : 8969059,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "   <h1> @ElementCollection </h1>\n<p>This annotation will be applied when there is a relation with non-entity and these associations relation was <strong>HAS-A</strong>. Every collection is created with a table and gets relation by <em>Foreign Key</em>.</p>\n<p>There are two types of element collections</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Index (List, Map)</li>\n<li>Non-Index (Set)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Index</strong>: The index type collection has a table with 3 columns they are</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Key Column (Foriegn Key)</li>\n<li>Index Column (Position of data in collection)</li>\n<li>Element Column (Data)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Non-Index</strong>: The Non-Index type collection has a table with 2 columns they are</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Key Column</li>\n<li>Element Column</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Note</em>: Here it won't have any index column because, Since a <strong>SET</strong> doesn’t retain the insertion order.</p>\n<h1>Multiplicity</h1>\nThis is a way to implement the HAS-A relation between two entities and the cardinality ratio depends on their relation. \n"
  } ],
